{"input": "[Neg · 1AR voting issues · 2NR] Why should we reject 1AR independent voting issues?", "output": "A] Time skew- They can blow up any 3 second argument into a 3-minute collapse no matter how long the 2nr spends on it making it a lose-lose situation for the negative\n\nB] Clash- Incentivizes lazy debating where debaters don’t interact with the actual sheets but instead chose to up-layer\n\nC] Psychology- they get a 2ar collapse which means the judge will always err towards what they say\n\nD] No Risk- They become no risk issues and they can read tons of them in the 1ar which splits the 2nr several ways\n\nE] Structural skew- they’re short 10 second no-risk arguments that all become massive nibs that endlessly split the 2nr", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR voting issues] Why should we get RVI’s on 1AR voting issues?", "output": "That’s key to preventing absurd voting issues that are just trivializing and an obvious attempt at the ballot. It also means the 1AR is more likely to develop their arguments instead of waiting for the 2AR which leads to late breaking and underdeveloped debates.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · IVI debate · 2NR] Why should we evaluate the IVI debate after the 2NR?", "output": "A] Reciprocity- it means we get one speech each B] Psychology- it hedges back against overly persuasive 2ars that will inevitably sway the judge C] Intuition- If what I did was really problematic then the judge would intuitively reject 2nr arguments", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · DTA on 1AR IVIs] Why should we use drop the argument on 1AR independent voting issues?", "output": "A] Negative Strategy- DTD allows them to up layer and moot 7 min of the NC forcing 2nr overallocation B] Substance- 2AR’s will be incentivized to take the easiest out and won’t be inclined to go for substance in the 2ar which makes the rest of the topic debate meaningless", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · reject combo shells · 2NR] Why should we reject combo shells?", "output": "A] It’s way too specific to this debate so it can’t generate norms in the future which is constitutive of theory. B] Encourages tacking on random planks that make generating counter interp offense impossible while making it difficult to quantify the abuse each plank solves. C] Reading separate shells on each issue solves their offense.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · DTA paradigm issues · 2NR] Why should we use drop the argument?", "output": "It’s most real-world since you wouldn’t give us the death penalty for jay-walking and allows us to go back to substance which outweighs since we only have 2 months to debate the topic. They have no spillover reason why the violation means you can’t engage in anything else.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · reject meta-theory · 2NR] Why should we reject meta-theory?", "output": "It’s infinitely regressive since we can keep reading theory on theory which outweighs since it’s a meta-constraint on the judge’s final jurisdiction.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · in round abuse outweighs · 2NR] Why does in round abuse outweigh norm setting?", "output": "In round abuse outweighs normsetting: A] Verifiability- you can’t verify norm setting occurs but you can verify in round abuse which outweighs B] Empirically denied- people lose to condo all the time and still read condo advocacies C] Culpability- anything else generates a bad norm of culpability that isn’t specific and leads to bad theory debates because anything could potentially justify anything.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · 1AR theory] Why should the aff get 1AR theory?", "output": "1AR theory is legit – anything else means infinite abuse – drop the debater, competing interps – 1AR are too short to make up for the time trade-off. 2] Reasonability on 1NC theory with the brightline of link and impact turn ground – there are infinite bidirectional interps that I can never meet – the four minute 1AR doesn’t have enough time to line by line every argument, make offense, and go for substance.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · Law of Excluded Middle] How does the law of excluded middles justify that permissibility affirms?", "output": "The Law of Excluded Middles states that if something is not false, it must be true. This implies that if something is not prohibited, it must be obligatory, and that permissibility is equivalent to being obligatory.", "category": "Philosophy", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · Debate Evaluation] Why should we evaluate the debate after the 2AR?", "output": "Evaluating the debate after the 2AR is important because failing to do so creates an unfair time skew for debaters and is arbitrary.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · comparative worlds] Why should we use comparative worlds over truth testing?", "output": "Use comparative worlds—forces the neg to research the topic instead of low quality rez flaw arg. Truth-testing allows the neg to disprove any part of the aff, but the aff has to defend every part, which isn’t reciprocal. Additionally, truth testing says the rez is only thing that’s relevant—either only the rez matters so we can’t punish slurs, or people should get dropped for making debate unsafe which proves other things matter.\n\nThis isn’t offense unless you read truth testing or logcon but\n\nA] Resolve is defined as, settle or find a solution to (a problem, dispute, or contentious matter) so the past tense, resolved, grammatically means the resolution has been resolved.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · presumption] Why should presumption affirm?", "output": "Even if the aff doesn’t solve necessarily EVERYTHING it’s a step in the right direction and absent offense about why [the topic] is bad that is extended in the 2NR there is a sufficient risk of offense to vote affirmative.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · PTIV] When I'm going for plan text in a vacuum, how do I answer the argument that I no linked out of their stuff?", "output": "Yes we no linked out of your stuff on the basis of us winning our definitions – if you were winning the definitions debate and extended an impact to the DA that outweighs and turns the case – you would have won the debate. But absent that – you err affirmative.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · framework 2AR] Why should we focus on models in this debate?", "output": "This debate is a question of models. Floating disadvantages aren’t offense. They must be tied to a model that resolves it.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · framework 2AR] Why should we preserve fidelity for the 2NR to the 1NC?", "output": "Unwarranted, blip storms shouldn’t be evaluated. You should especially preserve fidelity for the 2NR to the 1NC. That means new 2NR claims are scrutinized, and those without warrants are rejected. Anything else devolves into tricks debate.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · framework 2AR] I'm going for middle ground framework in the 2AR against the K. How should I summarize the benefits of my int4erpretation??", "output": "Our interpretation is the only one that is additive, not exclusive. It says consequences matter but does not limit how they engage.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · framework 2AR] Why does a 'you link, you lose' framework undermine fairness?", "output": "First is fairness – their model decks it by ensuring all topic prep, 1AC offense, and pretournament strategy are disregarded, which outweighs. It’s the only intrinsic impact since debate is a game. Its why they emphasize strategic concessions, ask you to evaluate arguments, its why judges don’t flip a coin, which proves it is tautological to say something outweighs fairness. Conceded.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · framework 2AR] Why does a 'you link, you lose' framework undermine clash?", "output": "Second is clash – it straight turns all their offense. Models that focus solely on epistemology encourage kritiks that read broad, unwarranted structural claims in order to generate the broadest links, which sidesteps iterative clash. Models that throw out consequences lead to links to words to the aff, links with zero impact, which proves the model of “you link, you lose” destroys clash.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · framework 2AR] Why does clash outweigh?", "output": "That outweighs. We are the only ones with research that prove the benefits of clash on subject formation. It’s key to break down dogmatism and facilitates the best form of testing and scrutiny. However, the only way to facilitate that is to “pass… questioning… in light of…consequences” and “evaluate… discourse… within a deliberative procedure”. It’s the best way to make us better political subjects outside of debate. That’s Fairclough.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · subjectivity and debate · 2NR] How does our argument about subjectivity affect the debate?", "output": "That’s key because no singular round affects subjectivity. Conceded. Even if I read China War Good one round, it doesn’t mean it affects my subjectivity because debate is a question of winning.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · state and genocide · 2NR] How do we respond to the argument that defending the state causes genocide?", "output": "Similarly, defending the state does not cause genocide, but the procedure of researched grounded in stasis means our impacts outweigh on ballot proximity.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · implications of debate · 2NR] Why does engaging in debate fairly matter for real-world implications?", "output": "That straight turns their offense. Debate might have implications outside of a game, but the only way to make those implications real or to actualize debates benefits is by engaging in it fairly.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · functionally intrinsic perms · 2NR] Why should we reject functionally intrinsic, textually non-intrinsic perms?", "output": "Reject functionally intrinsic, textually non-intrinsic perms---obviating functional difference through intrinsicness based on reordering words divorces words from context, which lets all hell break loose---turns debate into a word scramble, encouraging infinite unpredictable perms that deck engagement---teams will utilize large plan texts that contain all conjunctive nouns to connect all phrases.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · delay counterplans · 2NR] Why should we reject delay counterplans?", "output": "a. even though CPs could hypothetically delay, they have to generate a net benefit to a small delay to the aff which the aff can straight turn, impact turn, etc BUT the neg can’t do the same because affs can delay and force debates towards the future, where turns are also resolved---for example, heg bad turns are resolved by delaying until Russia collapses\n\nb. the aff has uniqueness and reasons why immediate action are key built in, which means strategic affs beat delay counterplans", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · counterplan theory · 2NR] How do we respond to the argument that our model incentivizes good counterplans?", "output": "We’ll preempt ‘our model incentivizes good counterplans’---their model eliminates all counterplans that are remotely relevant to the topic---most authors advocate policies like 50 states or partially open borders that could eventually lead to the aff, and cards about that exist for every counterplan---their model makes those counterplans non-competitive since any policy could result in the aff, making them compete off immediacy, which is bullshit---forces CPs to sabotage their solvency just to generate competition.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · process CPs bad theory · 2NR] Why does the argument about process counterplans being bad theory not hold?", "output": "There’s no offense---a theoretically illegitimate CP can be competitive---I’m sorry you can’t win on Process CPs bad theory---they can only win if they persuade you there exists some hypothetical delay CP that is so bad that you should reject all CPs that compete off immediacy, but that’s arbitrary and cherrypicked because it would be easy to prove individual instances are theoretically legitimate as well---proves it’s a sliding scale---the implication is THEY must win [Myanmar conditions CP theory], which would be new---this is a middle ground as it resolves cheating CPs and allows for neg ground.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · mooting inevitability · 2NR] Why is mooting inevitable in this debate?", "output": "Mooting is inevitable---they choose the aff, and Ks, T, and other CPs all do it---no reason ours specifically is a voter.", "category": "General", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · counterplans · 2NR] Why should we argue that counterplans should be functionally competitive?", "output": "Counterinterp: counterplans should be functionally competitive\n\n1] Literature distortion frames impact calculus---there’s a lack of neg ground and an unlimited topic with unbeatable affs means holding rejoinder to text keeps a dying negative in an enclosed cage---text and function can’t be a norm from topic to topic as research holds different weight for an aff or neg that NEED to be balanced. ONLY expanding rejoinder to function can elevate prep.\n\nDon’t bail out the 2AR’s inevitable list of CPs---that’s a balance required when one side is afforded infinite prep and literature distortion and at best for every CP they list we can list about 10 more affs and the caselist doesn’t exist in the 1AR.\n\n2] Testing---its debates only intrinsic value and is meta to fairness---crafting proposals is only possible through determining action based on mandate, since words only matter based on their effect---negs doesn’t read deterrence DA based on words of the plan BUT how countries perceive it.\n\nThat obviates all perms that compete off text but not function\n\nFunctional only doesn’t open the floodgates---their model justifies indicting adv CPs by saying ‘perm do both’, which doesn’t sever text which automatically makes the CP not competitive since competing off function is illegit---function encourages depth debates centered around the affirmatives chosen evidence, process, and core advantages.", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · e-deliberative branch · General] Why should we establish an e-deliberative branch of government that initiates debates in favor of the Justices of the Supreme Court being term-limited?", "output": "The United States ought to establish an e-deliberative branch of government that initiates debates in favor of the Justices of the Supreme Court being term-limited. The Executive and Legislative Branches should promulgate new regulations that require binding and genuine consultation with the e-deliberative branch on all decisions, including abiding by the outcome of the branch’s debates.", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · e-deliberation] Why should we assume the aff is implemented post-CP if they provide benefits?", "output": "The aff is implemented post-CP because e-deliberation has no reason to reject the aff if they’re right about benefits. It’s their burden to provide evidence that people would hate it – otherwise, we default to their own analysis of why the plan is good.", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · link turn to politics] Why should we concede that the aff is bipartisan from politics?", "output": "Conceding the aff is bipartisan from politics ensures it is approved – they can’t contradict their own polls.", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · CP outweighs] Why does the counterplan outweigh the affirmative's arguments about democracy and citizen involvement?", "output": "The CP outweighs – the aff doesn’t assume the heart of democracy is based upon relationship between government and the people, which is revitalized through preventing detachment between two – OUR argument is about citizen involvement – creating a new branch counterbalances current failures with the supreme court.", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · net benefit] Why does the counterplan not test the net benefit?", "output": "Doesn’t test net benefit – it adds extraneous factors of function to change meaning of the plan and counterplan to erase the net benefit.", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · permutation] Why can't we do both the permutation and the aff's plan?", "output": "(1) Can’t do both. The permutation either severs the aff going through existing political systems – that’s NC competition that aff normal means is constitutional amendment, which has to go through Congress, which is a voting issue – that was ALL of the work above. OR it goes through the three branches, which means it links to\n\n(A) Strike down – simultaneous action means that the aff gets struck down because e-deliberation is a prerequisite to political passage in the world of new regulations promulgated by the CP – that’s Papandreou. That means the three branches do not have the authority to initiate passage so the aff is illegal.\n\n(B) Law making – the CP does not fiat the plan but requires deliberation and abiding by the result of such – either the plan passes so there’s no debates OR the perm severs the mandate of the plan. Severance destroys ground and makes the aff a moving target.", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · fourth branch creation · 2NR] Why should we reject the argument that the second plank is coherent without the first plank creating the fourth branch?", "output": "The first plank is the one that CREATES the fourth branch, “second plank” in a vacuum is incoherent because the fourth branch hasn’t been created yet – reject hailmary on this, writing better perm texts solve.", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · civic participation · 2NR] Why does excluding the first plank mean the permutation can’t solve the net benefit related to civic participation?", "output": "They exclude the first plank, which has the branch initiate public debates, which are the internal link to civic participation – perm can’t solve net benefit.", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · strike down argument · 2NR] Why does simultaneous action mean the aff gets struck down due to e-deliberation being a prerequisite?", "output": "Strike down – simultaneous action means that the aff gets struck down because e-deliberation is a prerequisite to political passage in the world of new regulations promulgated by the CP – that’s Papandreou. That means the three branches do not have the authority to pass the aff so it’s declared illegal.", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · strike down links · 2NR] Why do we need to sever the permutation for solvency in relation to the strike down argument?", "output": "If strike down already read (3) Links to strike down since it requires simultaneous action with the plan – new regulations means the aff would have to be consulted over by the fourth branch and implemented by them, so the permutation requires severance for solvency.", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · perm sever] Why should we reject the perm sever for existing political systems?", "output": "All reasons why perm do both severs apply to perm do the CP – the perm severs existing political systems and using one of the existing three branches.", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · moral obligation · 2NR] Why should we extend our interpretation that 'ought' means a moral obligation?", "output": "Extend our interpretation that 'ought' means a moral obligation, which means they have to prove a moral obligation.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · jettisoning resolution · 2NR] Why does jettisoning any part of the resolution matter?", "output": "Jettisoning any part of the resolution is bad – it removes all constraints on preround prep, decking the only stasis point for debate.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · moral anti-realism · 2NR] Why is moral anti-realism true and moral realism false?", "output": "Moral anti-realism is true, and moral realism is false.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · evolution and morality · 2NR] How does evolution dictate our current worldview instead of abstract morality?", "output": "Evolution dictates our current worldview, not abstract morality. Their blum evidence indicates that our aversion to pain is purely biological and our pursuit of pleasure is also entirely biological.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · anti-scientific view of evolution · 2NR] Why is it problematic for the aff to defend an anti-scientific view of evolution?", "output": "That either means the aff has to defend an anti-scientific view of evolution, i.e. that evolution tracks morality instead of tracking survival, which is impossible given the fact that moral beliefs will die out if they are unfavorable, or that evolution doesn’t track morality, so all ethical beliefs humans currently hold are not true morality.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · litmus test for ethics · 2NR] Why is certainty and non-arbitrariness important for the litmus test for ethics?", "output": "C/a from case that the litmus test for ethics is certainty and non-arbitrariness – they meet neither because of the above analysis. Evolution is definitionally uncertain and arbitrary to survival conditions so they can't prove that their morality can guide actions in all hypothetical worlds.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · moral naturalism · 2NR] Why are all their arguments that moral naturalism solves wrong?", "output": "All their arguments that moral naturalism solves are wrong: Hume’s guillotine – naturalist ethics cannot cross the is/ought gap to prove that reasons are universal. Different individuals can deduce different things from different natural perspectives, which proves it can't cross the gap. That’s Hume.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · appearance/reality · 2NR] Why is distinguishing between morality appearing real and morality actually being real problematic?", "output": "Appearance/reality. Any subject has to distinguish between something being true and something appearing to be true. That’s impossible because to know X implies you can distinguish between X and Y, and to know morality assumes you can distinguish between morality appearing real and morality actually being real, which we can't do.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · impact justification · 2NR] Why should we reject their impact justified frameworks?", "output": "Its impact justified. Their extinction outweighs/pleasure good/pain bad arguments all boil down to pleasure is good because it's pleasurable, or pain is bad because it's painful, or extinction is bad because it causes extinction. Impact justified frameworks are a barren tautology. X thing is good simply means good things are good or pleasurable things are pleasurable which tells us nothing about the world and implies ethics wouldn’t be binding and are arbitrary since we can fill in x with anything.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · contingent ethics · 2NR] Why does the contingency of ethics imply that objective morality is impossible?", "output": "That means ethics are contingent, not objective, since if we had just evolved differently then our conception of morality would be different, so any objective morality is impossible and you can’t affirm a moral obligation to do the plan.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · time skew] Why should we compensate for the time skew in the debate structure?", "output": "Its k2 to compensate for the time skew - the time crunched 4 minute 1ar has to hedge against a 7 minute 1n and counter a 6 min 2nr collapse, no rvis kill the affs ability to win, anything else means the 2nr will kick theory and win substance b/c they are structurally ahead or will go for theory and win - o/w on scope - it affects the 1ar and 2ar - link turns logic - both sides need to have a chance at winning to have a logical debate", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Reciprocity] Why does reciprocity create a structural skew in the debate?", "output": "Reciprocity - the negative has the unique ability to win off T and theory while aff can only win on theory -- creates a 2-1 structural skew", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · No Risk Issue · 2NR] Why should we reject the no risk issue argument regarding RVIs?", "output": "No Risk Issue - No RVIs incentivizes the 1N/1AR to spam theory shells and go for the most undercovered shell. OWs baiting bc it’s empirically proven. Links to:\n\na] fairness bc it makes a time crunched 1AR almost impossible - either way the 1AR will undercover something & the 2N can go for either layer\n\nb] Norming - Makes it so theory is about finding the smallest education and fairness violations and reading theory on them since it’s a no risk issue - OWs bc people won’t see theory as a tool to check legitimate abuse but to win – and also enables\n\nNorming first - Even if no RVIs leads to slight fairness/ed violations it doesn’t matter since it destroys theory’s ability to set good norms in general - OWs on scope and magnitude since we can’t check for fairness/ed violations and illogical args.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Reciprocity · 2NR] Why does reciprocity matter in our argument against the 1AR?", "output": "Reciprocity - I have to respond to all shells to get to substance while they win off any shell - Reciprocity controls the strongest IL to fairness - its the definition of procedural fairness.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Logic] Why should we reject RVIs in the context of logic arguments?", "output": "Winning the CI means you falsely accused me of being unfair/educational and your interpretation creates bad norms for debate, so RVIs aren’t illogical - I’m not saying I should win for being fair - that’s not looking at the full picture. Turn - No RVIs make winning virtually impossible for the aff - every debate logically presumes somewhat equal ability to get the ballot. Non Unique + No Impact - debate has infinitely illogical practices like spreading, logic has no uniqueness or impact that o/w our fairness claims. No Brightline for what types of things are logical also means rvi can be logical given different interpretations of logic. Impact Weighing - Even if I’m being a bit illogical norming OW - structurally precludes ability to engage in the first place and we’re not destroying logic in general, just saying it’s not first in this specific instance.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Baiting/Chilling Effect] How do we respond to the argument that frivolous theory outweighs in the context of baiting?", "output": "Friv Theory outweighs - abusive 1ACs that bait theory still create productive theory debates that may create norms against bad practices - friv theory debates don’t create good norms and degrade theory. Legit abuse solves - if the 1AC is extremely abusive, the 1N has truth on their side and can easily win the theory debate even if they’re bad. No impact - people will read shells against 1ACs in a world without RVIs, no reason baiting is any worse. Impact turn - baiting means we debate theory more - leads to better norms because we set more rigorous norms. Non unique - you can just prep out the 2nr or common responses to your own shell. This isn't a reason we don't get rvis, debate works in a way in which you frontline different possible arguments.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Substantive Debate] How do we respond to the argument that the lack of impact from RVIs is the fault of the side supporting no RVIs?", "output": "No impact, and the side supporting no RVIs brought theory up in the first place - it’s their fault.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · logic] Why should we reject the argument that RVIs create good norms?", "output": "I’m not saying I win for being fair, rather it is structurally impossible for us to win, falsely accusing us is bad, my interpretation is better, and RVIs create good norms. No Brightline for what types of things are logical also means RVIs can be logical given different interpretations of logic.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · chilling effect / baiting] Why does it matter if the aff is abusive?", "output": "If the aff is actually abusive, it doesn't matter how much good they are, you’ll win either way - only bad theory is chilled. Non unique - you can just prep out the 2NR or common responses to your own shell – not their fault you don’t.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · time skew] Why should we argue that time skew is good?", "output": "If I’m really abusive it’s almost guaranteed you can win the theory debate and the round either way – just read theory on actual abuse. Time skew is good; it disincentivizes people from reading theory they know they won’t win on, which deters frivolous theory. Solved by the fact that people can read drop the arg.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · No RVI's] Why should we reject RVIs?", "output": "(a) creates a chilling effect – aff is dangerous on theory because they get to prep a long counterinterp in the 1ar and then get the 2ar to collapse, weigh, and contextualize - negs would always be disincentived from reading theory against good theory debaters which leads to infinite abuse so it outweighs time skew\n\n(b) they’re illogical - “I’m fair vote for me” doesn’t make any sense - you dont win for meeting ur burden of being fair - logic comes first on theory since all args need to make sense in order to be evaluable.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · DTD - k2 strategy] Why does the 2AR being too short to win theory and substance matter for our strategy?", "output": "The 2AR is too short to win theory and substance, which means we can’t check abuse since I inevitably lose the debate.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Drop the debater] Why should we drop the debater?", "output": "[a] Epistemic Skew - I was structurally precluded from engaging in substance given the time spent reading the shell and the abuse itself, means you can’t truly evaluate substance because they are always ahead [b] Deters Future Abuse - empirically confirmed with things like A Prioris [c] Norm Setting - anything else allows debaters to get away with abusive practices which means theory will never work at setting norms", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Epistemic Skew] Why should we reject the argument about epistemic skew?", "output": "[a] its reciprocal - it takes equal or more time actually responding to the shell proportionally, means there's no skew\n[b] there’s no reason they had to spend so much time on theory; their fault\n[c] even if dropping the argument would not fully rectify the “abuse,” it’s closer to being fair than dropping the debater\n[d] empirically disproven you’re engaging with the aff\n[e] begs the question", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · DTA norm setting] Why should we reject DTA normsets?", "output": "DTA normsets – debaters won’t read args, esp big positions, if they auto lose to theory shells – that’s not strategic. Turn - you overcompensate and set terrible norms where people lose rounds for minor violations.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Drop the Argument · 2NR] Why should we drop the argument on proportionality in the context of fairness violations?", "output": "Proportionality - it doesn't make sense to give the death penalty to someone who stole 1 piece of candy - that turns fairness and is net worse for it, it means that I would always lose for committing minor fairness violations like answering a question slowly in cross.\nTopic Ed - allows us to still debate the topic and get educational value from it, DTD throws away all potential topic ed that o/w. We only have 2 months to debate the topic. Sufficient defense on fairness means vote on ed otherwise it’d justify no ed over the smallest fairness violations.\nTheory Norming - DTD delegitimizes theory - it becomes used as a tool to win marginal violations and win rounds, that doesn't actually set any norms and kills theory’s value – Ows on scope since it means we can’t mediate fairness anded violations.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Proportionality · 1AR] Why should we reject the argument about resolvability in proportionality?", "output": "[1] Resolvability - theres no metric to determine how much a punishment is proportional to the abuse itself\n[2] Winning the shell link turns - it means you were abusive and massively skewed my strategy which is more than sufficient to DTD", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Theory Norming · 1AR] Why should we turn the argument about DTA?", "output": "[1] Turn - DTA means people just are infinitely abusive and concede the shell - wasting all the debaters time and also means no topic ed", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Theory Norming · 1AR] How do we respond to the argument that norms and theory are not mutually exclusive?", "output": "[2] Not Mutually Exclusive - you can set norms while still using theory as a ballot tactic", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · reasonability] Why should we use reasonability with a brightline for the arguments for reasonability?", "output": "Use reasonability with a brightline of the arguments for reasonability + defense on the interp being stronger than the interp’s offense - stops people from reading regressive shells and winning off marginal offense on them - their shell was regressive (insert justification if you want) - enables me to win on things like near terminal defense.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · reasonability] Why should we reject reasonability as arbitrary and interventionist?", "output": "reasonability’s arbitrary & forces judge intervention especially with 2ar recontextualizations to always sound like the more reasonable debater", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · norm setting] Why does norm setting matter in theory debates?", "output": "norm setting - we find the best possible norms through robust theory debates", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · reasonability collapses] What do we say to the argument that reasonability is a valid evaluation method?", "output": "reasonability collapses - you use offense/defense paradigm to evaluate brightlines, I’ll defend a norm setting model, anything else is arbitrary, infinitely regressive, and interventionist, theres no way to verify in round abuse", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · fairness] Why should we argue that fairness is a procedural constraint in the debate?", "output": "a] they concede the authority of fairness by agreeing to tournament procedures and speech times\n\nb] fairness is a procedural constraint—if they had 10 minutes to say fairness bad and I only had 1 minute to defend it, they would win because it was structurally unfair to begin with.\n\nc] every argument assumes the ability to be evaluated fairly and that the judge will take their position seriously\n\nd] if unfairness is good, you should be unfair against them and vote neg", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · fairness] Why does fairness come first in the debate?", "output": "Fairness controls the ability to gain respond to your args in the first place, if I had 1 second to respond to the 1ar I would lose due to fairness issues, also controls the internal link to education because we can't gain education if we’re precluded from good clash in the first place.\n\nVoting aff because their model is more educational doesn't gain you any actual educational value, however voting neg because they were unfair rectifies the abuse and has solvency.\n\nYour arguments presume the judge will evaluate them fairly, responses trigger a double bind in which either the judge does not evaluate your argument fairly and they can hack and vote neg or they do but that proves fairness comes first.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · importance of education] Why does education matter in the context of debate?", "output": "It’s the only reason schools fund debate - without it debate would not exist", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · terminal impact of debate] Why does education matter as the terminal impact of debate?", "output": "It’s the terminal impact of debate - only ed matters in the end which OW on longevity", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · fairness in debate] Why should debate be a coin flip for fairness?", "output": "Fairness first justifies debate being a coin flip", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · fairness vs education] Why should we prioritize education over fairness in debate?", "output": "Fairness is only instrumental to education: (a) If we had a fair game but no education happened, then there would be no reason for it to exist and (b) people create rules for debate to make the game more accessible for new debaters so they can get an educational benefit from the activity, but if I’m being educational that incentive is unnecessary.\n\nLongevity – education has values that transcend debate because we can use skills that we learn. The fairness of a particular round is limited just to that one round, but education has an impact on the rest of our lives.\n\nDebate is meaningless without education. The fairest way of doing debate would be flipping a coin since it accounts for resource disparities, side advantages, etc, but that’s a bad model since we don’t learn about anything. But obviously that’s not the point—at the end of the day, the reason we all do debate is because of the educational benefits behind the activity.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · normsetting] Why should we prioritize normsetting even if it leads to slight fairness/ed violations?", "output": "Even if my interp leads to slight fairness/ed violations it doesn’t matter if I win that theirs destroys theory’s ability to set good norms in general - OWs on scope and magnitude since we can’t check for fairness/ed violations. Debate is constituted of its norms - means good norms is a pre-req to debate being valuable in the first place - obviously if debate", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · Accessibility] Why should accessibility be prioritized as an independent voter that outweighs?", "output": "Accessibility is an independent voter that outweighs:\n\na] all benefits to their interp for fairness or something are implicit benefits to debating’s process or content debate that must be accessed\n\nb] this is a space constitutively designed to include different people by definition, so they void a fundamental structure of debate that comes before gateway issues\n\nc] most proximate obligation which outweighs on specificity – you are an educator and most of all have to prevent dropping out. \nd] schools wouldn’t fund it and no one would participate if it were repugnant - It also turns and outweighs fairness because it’s a structural barrier that can’t be solved via other means like getting faster, and because the most unfair thing is to be structurally excluded from even being in the room", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · 1AR theory] Why should we extend 1AR theory first?", "output": "A] Strat skew – short 2AR means I need to collapse to one layer to counter the long 2N collapse\n\nB] Epistemic Indict – if the 1N was abusive then my ability to respond was skewed so you can’t truly evaluate the 1nc\n\nC] Investment – it’s a much larger strategic loss because 1min is ¼ of the 1AR vs 1/7 of the 1NC which means there’s more abuse if I’m devoting a larger fraction of time\n\nD] Magnitude - the 1nc has 7 minutes of potential abuse whereas I have 6", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · strat skew · 2NR] Why should we reject the argument that strat skew is empirically disproven?", "output": "Strat skew empirically disproven - affs beat back 1N shells all the time and still win the rd off their shell - OWs on verifiability", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · epistemic indict · 2NR] How do we respond to the epistemic indict regarding the 1N being slightly abusive?", "output": "Epistemic Indict - If the 1N was slightly abusive it doesn’t justify the aff being super abusive and doesn’t moot the entirety of the 1N - that’s irreciprocal - lexicality turns", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · investment · 2NR] Why does the investment argument matter in this debate?", "output": "Investment - incoherent that’s like saying if I make bad strategic decisions vote aff - your fault you spent time on a dumb shell", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · magnitude · 2NR] How do we respond to the argument about magnitude in relation to the 1N?", "output": "Magnitude - doesnt mean I was abusive through the whole 1N - just look at the specific shells", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Theory First · 1NC] Why should we prioritize theory first in the debate?", "output": "[1] Lexicality - their abuse happened prior to my abuse, means that [a] you cannot truly evaluate other abuses - its epistemically skewed [b] it means my abuse was justified insofar that I had to be abusive to combat their abuse\n\n[2] Norming - we get 3 speeches to norm over the shell, while 1ar theory allows us only 2 means that [a] o/w on probability that the shell is true - we debated the 1n norm rigorously [b] we get more theory education which o/w on scope", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1N abuse · 1AR] Why should we cross-apply affirming harder against claims of 1N abuse?", "output": "If I was slightly abusive it doesn’t justify massive amounts of 1N abuse that’s irreciprocal and you can still tell whether they’re being too abusive.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR theory · 1AR] Why does debating 1N norm rigorously not prove it’s true and justify 1AR theory first?", "output": "Debating 1N norm rigorously doesn’t prove it’s true - also justifies 1AR theory first since you have 13 mins on your shell while I only have 7 - no impact to theory ed and false we can still debate your shell under my model - it’s ab arg qual not amount of speeches.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · T] Why should we vote on T first to establish norms before a topic change?", "output": "We only have 2 months to establish norms for the topic because after that it changes. Yet for theory we have an unlimited amount of time to establish norms. Thus, vote on T first in order to establish norms before a topic change.", "category": "Topicality", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · T] Why does T constrain theory?", "output": "T constrains theory. If we can combat abuse that particularly stems from the nature of the topic, it’ll help us address more generic theoretical concerns.", "category": "Topicality", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · T] Why does T outweigh on magnitude?", "output": "T outweighs on magnitude - the rez structures the entirety of the debate while small shells don’t involve every part of it.", "category": "Topicality", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · T] What do we say to the argument that the aff did the better debating?", "output": "The ballot asks you to vote for who did the better debating, but if the aff isn’t topical then you can’t say the aff did the better debating because they’re not actually affirming.", "category": "Topicality", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · evaluate shells] Why should we evaluate shells on the magnitude of abuse regardless of sides?", "output": "Evaluate shells on magnitude of abuse irregardless of sides - that means voting for the shell with comparatively more abuse:\n\na] otherwise debaters will be incentivized to read shells critiquing small practices of their opponent and spamming reasons why affirming/negating is harder instead of engaging with their opponent’s shells - kills normsetting and enables people to get away with abuse.\n\nb] 1N/1AR theory first doesn’t take into account round particularities - i.e. if aff wins affirming is harder generally but the aff was so abusive it made negating almost impossible/destroyed debate clearly the neg should win the round - OW on specificity.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · competing interpretations · 1AR] Why should we frame the competing interps debate through a lens of sufficient offense?", "output": "Frame the competing interps debate through a lens of sufficient offense - don’t let them win off marginal offense on the interp, - stops people from finding very small abuse and reading theory on it, especially thru links of omissions - to win their interp, they need to prove there was massive abuse, otherwise all abuse is outweighed by a) the time I spent beating their shell b) the bad norms they create c] proves there is no uniqueness claim", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · norms creation model] Why should we prefer a norms creation model of competing interpretations?", "output": "Prefer a norms creation model of competing interps, in which you defend a norm being good or bad based on all potential applications and benefits of said norm:\n\n[1] Resolvability - no way to determine how much abuse happened in the round because it’s not tangible, means we need to debate if the norm itself is good or bad\n\n[2] Norm Setting - anything else allows debaters to get away with infinitely abusive practices because they will make arbitrary and self serving arguments as to why in round they were not abusive - norm setting is the terminal impact to theory & the reason it was created in the first place\n\n[3] Accessibility - holistic applications allow debaters to rigorously create and set norms to make debate a safer space - anything else is too round-dependent and fails to improve debate, accessibility o/w its k2 debating in the first place", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · competing interpretations] Why should we prefer an in round abuse model of competing interpretations?", "output": "Prefer an in round abuse model of competing interps, in which you evaluate abuse based off how it structurally affected debaters in the round: [1] Infinite Abuse - norms creation means I always lose to practices that are out of my control, it's like saying “drop them for speaking, it can be potentially racist to speak” - I shouldn’t be held culpable to something I didn’t do", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · Infinite Regress] Why does their model of debate kill theory norming and make debate inaccessible and unsafe?", "output": "their model of debate means debaters always read shells with marginal offense that are too abstract that [a] kills theory norming [b] makes debate inaccessible and unsafe", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · Prefer Text over Spirit] Why should we prefer text over spirit in arguments?", "output": "[1] Verifiability - there's no way to determine the spirit of an argument, we only have the text two impacts [a] makes the round irresolvable because the judge doesnt know what it means to evaluate spirit [b] infinite abuse - you will just say the spirit is something completely different\n\n[2] Double bind - either [a] its okay to let the judge evaluate arguments that weren't actually made, thus you evaluate these screenshots below or [b] it isn't ok which means you don't evaluate the spirit given that you never said in your original speech what constituted the spirit", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · theory · 1AR] Why should we reject the argument that incentivizes infinite abuse in the 1AR?", "output": "Incentivizes infinite abuse – they’ll just fill the aff with unfair args at no risk and kick or reclarify it if I ask and just auto-win if I miss it – this means in other debaters where didn’t catch it, you would still win all your rounds due to non-debate motor skills and your unclarity which causes infinite unfairness which annihilates community norms.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · disclosure · 1AR] Why does disclosure matter in the context of the 1AR?", "output": "Disclosure – if I don’t know before the debate what your aff does I can’t make a strategy which gives you coaching advantages and a massive prep advantage – it also screws community norms because people don’t know how to shape plans to have the most topical fair advocacy according to consensus.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AC text best · 1AR] Why should we prioritize the AC text over memorizing CX?", "output": "AC text best – we can hold you to it but don’t memorize CX – that encourages vagueness which kills fairness and allows 1ar reclarifications which crushes my ground.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · topic specific theory debates · 1AR] Why are topic specific theory debates beneficial?", "output": "Topic specific theory debates are good (a) understanding what the words in the topic mean is a prerequisite to actually debating and understanding the topic, which link turns their friv theory args, (b) Theory debates allow us to create norms for future debates to be more fair and educational. Impact turns any argument about cx checks avoiding theory.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · CX time · 1AR] Why is CX time important in the context of the 1AR?", "output": "CX time – they incentivize easy stalling – CX time is key these days since affs are filled with confusing weird stuff, which destroys engagement if I can’t figure it out.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · content education · 1AR] Why does content education matter in the 1AR?", "output": "Content education – we don’t know their aff until CX so we start learning at the 8 minute mark not beginning which is net worse.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · judges attention in CX · 1AR] Why does the judges' attention in CX matter for the 1AR?", "output": "Judges don’t pay attention in cx – so it solves none of the abuse and shell outweighs.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · meta theory · 2NR] Why should we reject meta theory arguments in the 1AR?", "output": "Incentives abuse-debaters will read unfair stuff to bait theory and then read meta theory in the 1AR-kills fairness since the aff will do infinite abusive things. Sets terrible norms b/c no one will read theory meaning every will be abusive.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · infinite regress · 2NR] Why does infinite regress in meta theory arguments matter?", "output": "We can keep reading meta-theory args infinitely, the bright line to stop at is theory since it is still discussing substance. Once we move to metatheory then all substantial arguments are avoided and the round’s irresolvable since there can be infinite shells-resolvability is key since every debate needs a winner and outweighs since that’s a constitutive function of your role, other things are external.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · unreciprocal meta theory · 2NR] Why is the unreciprocal nature of meta theory arguments a problem?", "output": "Meta theory is unreciprocal-they can read meta theory in the 1AR and 2AR but I can only read it in the 2NR-gives you a 2-1 advantage that makes it easier for you to win structurally, outweighs your args since the layer you have is unavailable to me even if it’s good, reciprocity internal link turns your args since it’s the definition of fairness, anything not about equal access can be solved by other stuff.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · dropping arguments · 2NR] Why should we argue that meta theory can only justify dropping arguments?", "output": "Even if meta theory is relevant, it can only be a reason to drop the argument. The drop the debater claims on theory prove that substance was skewed so there’s nowhere else to vote, but your shell only proves that theory was skewed which means that we can still look back down to substance.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · clash with meta theory · 2NR] Why does meta theory matter in debates?", "output": "Meta theory causes a race to the highest layer where people run away from substance if they are afraid of debating it-kills education and advocacy skills since we don’t need to discuss the topic, advocacy skills turns your standards since it translates fairness into life abilities, without it there’s no impact.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · logic of theory vs substance · 2NR] Why does the distinction between theory and substance matter?", "output": "The difference between theory and substance arises because theory informs which substantive arguments matter. This means you can only get a theoretical violation from substance, not other theory since the theory practice indicts are just the same exact args as in the other shells, takes out your preclusions.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · weighing arguments in theory · 2NR] Why can we weigh arguments from theory shells against metatheory shells?", "output": "Even if meta theory is legitimate, it does not preclude normal theory. You can weigh arguments from theory shells to metatheory shells since they both impact back to the same way of structuring debate. If I’m winning that my shell better upholds fairness then a metatheory shell with a smaller link to fairness is meaningless.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · reject combo shells] Why should we reject combo shells?", "output": "1] strat skew – interps with a million planks are functionally nibs. If each plank is something I do that’s bad, losing that any one is a bad practice means I lose on theory, but if I win that the practice is good or solves their abuse they’ll just say that its bad when combined with the other stuff. Every plank allows them to make my practice good arguments non-unique. They can win off of each practice being bad, but I can’t win that anything but all of them together is good that includes every number of a potentially huge number of planks.\n\nOutweighs since every theory arg is a gateway issue I can lose on, but each arg is no risk, so each extra plank is unturnable offense which makes me autolose, outweighs substantive practices which don’t come first as well as turnable theory abuse.\n\n2] Resolvability – if I’m winning offense to one plank and you are winning to another, there’s no way to weigh those planks because your interp has to include both.\n\n3] Norm Setting – the probability that the same abuse occurs in any other round is miniscule because they indict so many practices – there’s no chance at setting a norm.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · T debate · 2NR] Why should we win the evidence debate to win the T debate?", "output": "They need to be winning the evidence debate to win the T debate because the evidence controls what are legitimate interpretations of the topic:\n\n(a) answering back the standards is insufficient to win the T debate because text constrains what is relevant topical ground in the first place\n\n(b) picking a random interpretation that lacks solid backing by an author or institution supercharges the abuse and\n\n(c) just winning pragmatic reasons to vote for you is not sufficient- those are just reasons why we should change the topic not adapt to your non T aff.", "category": "Topicality", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR theory] Why should we reject 1AR theory as illegitimate?", "output": "1ar theory is illegitimate –\n\nA] 1ar theory time skews the rest of the round since they have the 1ar and 2ar, which is 7 minutes compared to my 2nr, which is 6 minutes. This gives them a whole minute advantage on the theory debate, that’s a lot in such a time crunched event and outweighs their strat stuff since I need time to execute strat and get ground.\n\nB] the 2ar has 3 uncontested minutes on theory so the aff can to collapse to any dropped arg and weigh, which means the 2n can never cover all the 1ar args enough to win, that means the neg always loses but their abuse args supposedly outweigh mine so I can’t win at all, so the abuse outweighs their abuse since I lose on the highest layer.\n\nC] it forces new but inevitable responses to the counterinterp, which invites judge intervention – that outweighs infinite abuse because the judge randomly decides not based on debaters’ arguments, but at least infinite abuse is premised upon arguments made in round and is under the control of us\n\nNot line by lining these proves my collapsing abuse args and that those outweigh their abuse, so they’d autolose", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR theory] Why should we drop the argument on 1AR theory?", "output": "Drop the arg on 1ar theory – that means drop _______\n\nA] the 1ar will always be incentivized to go for theory because they get a ballot implication, destroying substance engagement\n\nB] You shouldn’t stake the round on incomplete 1ar blips that become 3 minute 2ars – that wrecks neg win percentage because it means the 2nr has to overcover 1 second arguments", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR theory] Why should we evaluate the 1AR theory debate directly after the 2NR is over?", "output": "Eval the 1ar theory debate directly after the 2nr is over - that means you dont evaluate the 2ar on the 1ar shell debate:\n\n[a] Reciprocity - we both get 1 speech anything else is a 2-1 skew\n\n[b] infinite abuse - there's no 3nr to respond to the 2ar, which means they always win due to my lack of ability to uphold my model of debate", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · theory debate · 2NR] Why should we evaluate the theory debate after the 2NR and not give credence to 2AR arguments?", "output": "Eval the theory debate after the 2nr – all decisions relating to fairness or education arguments should be made after the 2nr occurs – don’t give credence to 2ar arguments:\n\n[1] I don’t have a 3nr to respond to the 2ar, so the 2nr has to be both forward and backward looking, which makes collapsing super hard.\n\n[2] Double bind – either the 2ar arg was new which means it shouldn’t be evaluated because I can’t respond or the 2ar arg was in the 1ar so it shouldn’t matter if you eval after the 2nr because you already have the 1ar argument.\n\n[3] 2ar args weighing will be new and will be conceded so the judge will artificially grant it more credence because there was no response.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · framing issue] Why should we drop them for violating their own shell?", "output": "That means you should drop them -\n\n[a] Normsetting - by contradicting their shell, they are not only destroying the ability to set their specific norm, but theory normsetting in general - people won’t follow norms if the creators of them violate them, and people will start seeing theory as a cheap tool to win instead of tool to set real norms – that OWs on scope since it means theory will never be able to resolve abuse – also on specificity because they lead to the negative impacts they critique\n\n[b] Premeditated – Them violating OWs me violating since they knew it was wrong yet still did it - i.e. if you knew stealing was wrong but still did it, that’s net worse than a kid taking candy from a store when they don’t know better", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · truth testing rotb · 1AR] Why should we reject the interpretation that the 1AC must take a stance on truth testing in the AC or cross-ex?", "output": "Interpretation if the 1AC reads a truth testing rotb they must take a stance in the AC or in cross-ex whether it precludes theory or grant neg the choice to clarify it.\n\nViolation they didn’t.\n\nStandards\n\n[1] Shiftiness – If the 1N reads theory, 1AR can say TT precludes it, mooting all of the negative’s theory ground, and if the 1N doesn’t read it, the aff gets away with abuse, which OWs on magnitude - it means affs always win.\n\n1N responding to the TT ROB doesn’t solve since the 1AR can either dump on the ROB or win the theory shell if the neg over allocates on the ROB - either way, the aff gets huge time tradeoff destroying fairness.\n\n[2] Norming - makes theory debates devolve into debates over whether or not truth testing precludes theory -- the 1N is forced to over allocate on TT if they want theory to be a viable out, meaning they undercover the theory debate proper. If the 1N slightly undercovers the ROB, the 1AR and 2N will mostly be the ROB, meaning either way 'theory debates' don’t become about theory anymore - destroys normsetting bc people will not think of theory as a good norming tool and way less robust norms will be set.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · T-FX] Why should we reject the affirmative's claim that their policy action is not certain to pass?", "output": "Interpretation - the affirmative must not claim that the policy action of the affirmative is not certain to pass and that it wont pass immediately. To clarify, the aff cannot fiat a policy that does not happen for sure and that doesn’t happen now.\n\nViolation it isn’t\n\nStandards\n\n[1] - shiftiness - incentivize the aff to be shifty and change the timeline of the affirmative depending on the args neg reads in the 1N which OWs bc there’s never a stable statis point for the neg debater and they lose all their args.\n\n[2] Ground - they destroy common neg ground that depend on uniqueness like politics DAs or war scenarios by saying the aff will happen later which means affs will almost always win their advantages.", "category": "Topicality", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · unified solvency advocate] Why should we require a unified solvency advocate that agrees with all the specifications of our advocacy?", "output": "Interpretation: If the affirmative delineates specific functions of its advocacy as normal means i.e. enforcement, actor, definitions of laws, etc, then it must have a unified solvency advocate that agrees with all those specifications.\n\nViolation: Courts are normal means\n\nUnconditional means preventing from adding additional exceptions to international law.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal", "flag": "warrant_only"}
{"input": "[Aff · limits · General] Why should we argue that not having a unified solvency advocate allows us to choose any permutation of specifications?", "output": "Not having a unified solvency advocate that agrees with all your “normal means” specifications allows you to choose any permutation of specifications which explodes neg prep burden. Unified solvency advocates grant sufficient aff flexibility while still ensuring a reasonable case list since specification all comes from one source.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · ground · General] Why does the ability to choose any permutation of definitions and mechanisms benefit us in the debate?", "output": "They can choose any permutation of best definition for unconditional, recognition, AND right to strike that suites them, the best enforcement mechanism, the actor, and anything else all with any exceptions they want in conjunction with each other which makes it really easy for them to delink core negative ground like enforcement das, circumvention das, process cp, etc which is supercharged by no normal means on the topic.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · interpretation · 1AC] Why should we require the aff to explicitly specify a comprehensive advocacy text in the 1AC?", "output": "The aff must clarify how their offense links back to the role of the ballot, whether it is post-fiat or pre-fiat offense, and provide a clear explanation of the advocacy’s actor, action, and object. This ensures that the debate is grounded in a clear understanding of the aff's position and its implications.", "category": "Topicality", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · link turns the aff · 2NR] Why should we argue that link turns the aff because their impacts are premised on engaging with issues of oppression?", "output": "Your impacts are premised on engaging with issues of oppression, but no one will take seriously a position that can’t be clashed with.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · strategy skew · 2NR] Why does strategy skew matter in the context of the 1AR?", "output": "You can recontextualize your advocacy to make up reasons why my links and offense don’t link in the 1AR.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal", "flag": "warrant_only"}
{"input": "[Neg · framing · 2NR] How do we respond to the aff excluding our shell?", "output": "You can’t use the aff to exclude my shell. My shell simply constrains how you read your advocacy. My method is your advocacy with specification, so if I’m winning comparative offense, the shell outweighs even if method debates in general preclude theory.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR theory · 2NR] Why should we reject the interpretation that aff theory is drop the debater, no RVIs, Competing Interps and Aff theory first, and no new 2NR paradigm issues?", "output": "Interpretation – Debaters may not read that aff theory is drop the debater, no RVIs, Competing Interps and Aff theory first, and no new 2NR paradigm issues.\n\nViolation – Their UV\n\n1] Standards –\n\na] Infinite Abuse - They can read a theory shell that’s DTD/no RVI/CI where their standard automatically comes before any 1NC standard or shell because aff is always highest layer. So, I’ll auto lose to every 1AR shell since I can’t get offense on the highest layer. They can make new 1AR paradigm issues like eval the theory debate after the 1AR and I auto-lose because I don’t get new paradigm issues.\n\nb] Clash – I can’t clash if I always lose, and I can’t offensively engage on the highest layer which destroys theoretical clash – strongest I/L to education because it’s the only form of unique education we get from debate.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · unconditional advocacy · 1AR] Why should we vote aff to rectify a massive skew in the debate?", "output": "Interp and violation: advocacies must be unconditional – theirs isn’t\n\nVote aff to rectify a massive skew - [a] they force the 1ar to debate themselves, e.g. they can read a cp that solves heg and a heg impact turn on case means inevitably the 1ar has to contradict themselves - that allows the 2nr to always win b/c they cherry pick one of them [b] clash double bind - if i overcover the advocacies they just kick out of all my offense i make i.e turns/perms, which kills the time crunched 1ar, and if i undercover it they go for it. That also link turns education, we don't get any if they always win due to heavily under contested arguments & we can’t have meaningful depth on arguments. Dispo solves – ensures sufficient neg flex while enabling 1ar decision making.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · condo · 2AR] Why should we go for fairness offense in the 2AR regarding condo?", "output": "2ar is condo going for fairness offense they didn’t read education first, means fairness comes first because it’s a procedural constraint to evaluating the round and participation, skews the rest of the round which means you cant eval anything absent fairness since it’s uneven. Here’s why condo is abusive: the double bind which makes the 1ar impossible. Even 1 condo advocacy can be leveraged to moot massive amounts of the 1ar. Heres how: they read a conditional advocacy like an alt or a counterplan, the 1ar spends time putting method disads or perms on it. If the 1ar overcovers, they’ll just kick out of it meaning i lose all my offense on the advocacy and if i put too little, they’ll go for offense under the alt or the counterplan and win. Unconditionality solves bc the 2n has to go for the CP or weigh other args in the round over offense on it or perms which means there’s some 2n time investment to make up for 1ar investment. Outweighs bc 6-4 time skew. That also demonstrates no world under condo is educational – positions are just a means to strategy and there’s no meaningful clash since you always go for undercovered args.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · condo · 2AR] Why does too much neg flex make it impossible to affirm?", "output": "Neg flex - too much flex makes it impossible to affirm while negs beat affs without condo shells. You can read multiple disads or an unconditional alt. You have 7 mins to uplayer a 6 min 1ac and a 6 min collapse -- not necessary to solve 2ar judge adv because you can weigh any other position. Strat skew also OWs -if im winning my args it proves it goes too far and makes it almost impossible to affirm.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · education arguments · 2AR] How do we respond to the education arguments about condo?", "output": "Education args - 1] turn: affs will always spread themselves thin in the 1ar and undercover something destroying meaningful clash. 2] disincentivizes good cps because negs dont have to go for them under condo – being forced to defend an advocacy makes you read strong positions. Testing is nonunique - you can test with disads, & it’s meaningless absent in depth clash on it. Defensive or explanatory reasons for why neg flex, testing, etc. weren’t relevant as you’re extending the story. This turns all their education arguments - demonstrates no world within condo that has a good substantive debate because either option is unsubstantive.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · plan inclusive counterplan · 2NR] Why should we vote aff for predictable ground?", "output": "Interpretation: The negative debater must not read a plan inclusive counterplan or an advocacy that includes part of the affirmative plan.\n\nViolation - they did.\n\nVote aff for Predictable Ground – incentivizes stealing the aff with the most minor changes I can’t predict or frontline around which OWs on magnitude since it’s impossible to affirm -- they’ll just find trivially true PICs and weigh or prep out the debate on the PIC. There’s also no clash since it promotes ignoring affs which is constitutive to debate – controls the internal link to education bc it under limits debate to something minuscule, i.e. mosquitos, instead of the main args on the topic.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · counterplan solvency · 2NR] Why should we vote aff for predictable limits?", "output": "If the neg reads a counterplan that includes a part of the plan, they need a unified solvency advocate that advocates for the entirety of the counterplan – they didn’t explain. Vote aff for predictable limits – there are infinitely many possible permutations of things that you could PIC out of, which makes aff prep impossible and causes cherrypicking - supercharged by the fact that it moots the aff so I can’t weigh the case. A solvency advocate checks by putting a reasonable limit on aff preparation in the context of a response to the aff because I’ll just have to prep out ACTUAL topic lit – also key to education because policymakers don’t propose plans with random things taken out, they do it based on advocacies that have been made in literature before.", "category": "CP", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · consult counterplans] Why should we vote aff against consult counterplans?", "output": "Interp: counterplans can’t include the possibility of doing the aff advocacy, i.e. consult counterplans\nviolation if the groups say yes they do the whole aff,\nVote aff – it steals the AC and forces the debate to whether they’ll say yes because I can’t leverage the aff, eliminates half my speech time and restarts the debate in the 1ar so I can’t win - also makes it impossible to formulate a strat if they don’t specify whether or not it leads to the aff bc I don’t know what counts as offense", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · process counterplans] Why should we reject process counterplans?", "output": "Interp: counterplans can’t include the possibility of doing the aff advocacy, i.e. process counterplans\n\nviolation they do the aff but through a different process\n\nvote aff – it steals the entirety of the AC with the tiniest changes that are marginally better - the aff can’t prep for it because there’s an infinite amount of different processes they could take and they moot all of the 1AC speech time because they’re still using the aff’s advantages, giving the neg a huge time advantage – links to fairness and ed, perms don’t solve because CPs will be made unpermable and no risk.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · condo] Why should we reject the negative's counterplan for using the same words as the affirmative advocacy?", "output": "Interpretation: All negative advocacies must be mutually exclusive with the affirmative advocacy and must not include the words of the aff advocacy in their advocacy text.\n\nViolation: they use the same words as the AC in their CP\n\nGround - they can moot the aff by making a CP the words of the aff and adding another plank, auto solving the aff advocacy along with something else which destroys 6 mins of the 1AC", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · competing interpretations · 2NR] Why should we reject their competing interpretations if they don't specify offense/defense or norms creation?", "output": "Interp: Debaters reading competing interps must specify in a text if it means offense defense, and if it means norms creation.\n\nB Violation: they just read it without specifying anything – even if some args support one or another, you aren’t held to that, that ambiguity is my link arg.\n\nStrat: they can spike out of norming counterinterp args – those matter for substantive issues to win theory but also to meta issues like drop the arg and rvis whether norming applies across rounds, or whether it’s just this round. If I make only a few defensive args, they might say it implies offense defense, which reduces my strat. Not knowing which is which let’s the 2nr pick which is too late and forces strat predications on some component that may not exist. 1ar prep and cx are really crunched due to high volume, especially for theory since it comes first.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · theory interps · 2NR] Why should we reject theory interpretations that contain more than 2 planks?", "output": "Interp and violation: theory interps must contain a max of 2 planks. To clarify, they cannot say that I cannot do three or more different practices at once – look their interp.\n\nStrat: interps with a million planks are functionally nibs. If each plank is something I do that’s bad, losing that any one is a bad practice means I lose on theory, but if I win that the practice is good they’ll just say that it’s bad when combined with the other stuff. If I win any combination of two practices is good, they’ll say it doesn’t assume the other independently bad plank. Every plank allows them to make my practice good arguments non-unique. Use past experience for how these shells play out – it’s always used to win off each practice being bad but so that the other can’t win that anything but all of them together is good that includes every number of a potentially huge number of planks. Outweighs since every theory arg is a gateway issue I can lose on, but each arg is no risk, so each extra plank is unturnable offense which makes me autolose, outweighs substantive practices which don’t come first as well as turnable theory abuse.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · theory · 2NR] Why should we reject their theory interp and violation for not writing it down explicitly?", "output": "Debaters must completely and explicitly write theory interps down before they read it, they didn’t. Strat – Stable “I meet” and competitive counter-interps, and they can shift their offense and violation thresholds in the next speech, without which I’ll easily lose – even if you “get the gist” you can’t call the interp to resolve a disagreement, independent resolvability impact that outweighs and is it’s own voter since every round constitutively must have a winner. Cross-x doesn’t check they can morph violations based on previous qs or if they change their mind.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · theory · 2NR] Why does their prep skew matter in this debate?", "output": "They force prep wasting asking about explicit texts since high speed flowing makes getting every word impossible – outweighs in theory debates as one mis-step or bad wording means an insta-loss because it comes before anything.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · theory · 2NR] Why should we reject the Aff's multiple theory voters argument?", "output": "Interp: Debaters with multiple theory voters can’t a) refuse to specify what voter is the most important in their original shell and also b) deny an RVI\n\nViolation: they did both – fair version is either just not both\n\n[1] Aff strat – they’ll just go for what I undercover, and no RVIs means I don’t have time to weigh and you can just do it all in the 2N and crush me since most of my speech was irrelevant, and if I do weighing then they’ll just go for substance\n\n[2] Intervention – no comparisons force interventions, but new 2N args also force intervention since it’s arbitrary how much weight you give totally new but required 2AR answers – it wouldn’t be your fault, but you’d have to do something like it to decide – biggest fairness impact since their offense assumes objective judging, and because who wins is unrelated to debating done which is the most possible unmeritable result.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · stable advocacy] Why should we vote aff for stable advocacy?", "output": "Interp: the neg must read an advocacy text in the 1nc – they didn’t\n\nVote aff for stable advocacy – the neg can shift functionality, mooting 1AR applicability, forces a 1ar time split between infinite possible advocacies, and causing 1ar incoherence which outweighs because of 7-4 and the burden of rejoinder. That independently causes judge intervention – determining what their actual advocacy is is left up to the judge, which causes intervention which is the worst form of unfairness because it completely takes the debate out of the debaters’ hands.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · advocacy status · 1NC] Why should we reject the neg's advocacy if they didn't specify its status in a delineated text in the 1NC?", "output": "Interp: If the neg reads an advocacy, they must specify the status of that advocacy in a delineated text in the 1NC.\n\nViolation – they didn’t\n\nThe standard is strat skew – they make 1ar preparation impossible because I have to plot the 1ar strategy based on 3 different worlds which makes the 1ar impossible – there’s already a devastating time skew so the 1ar needs adequate strategy construction to even have a chance. And, CX doesn’t check because judges don’t flow and stalling supercharges our abuse story.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · object fiat] Why does object fiat matter?", "output": "That’s constitutive and outweighs since otherwise this is original oratory – we have to be able to have a stable basis for arguments – it’s also the basis for all permutations and solvency deficits which has greater severity.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · object fiat] Why should we act based on my uniqueness about object fiat?", "output": "My uniqueness says we need to act because others aren’t, which they neatly do – that’s the definition of fiating the object of the plan – I can’t win since they’ll always scoop the aff.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · real world] Why does the real world matter for education and fairness?", "output": "No policymaker could have the choice between doing something and having Japan or the courts do it instead. Real world key to education since education that isn’t real world isn’t even education since it couldn’t affect what we actually learn, and key to fairness since all args assume a stable basis of the real world for ground.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · framework ks · 2NR] Why should we vote aff against framework Ks?", "output": "Interpretation: The neg may not derive a route to the ballot premised on the flaws of the aff framework. To clarify, framework ks are bad.\n\nViolation:\n\nVote aff:\n\n[1] Reciprocity – they can win by disproving the aff framework, but we have to win framework and substance, which is a 2-1 burden. That outweighs – a] strength of link – fairness definitionally is about routes to the ballot, which reciprocity controls b] structural – other stuff can be combatted via stuff like better arguments, but structural abuse skews evaluation\n\n[2] Strat skew – they moot half of the ac, which wrecks substance education – independently means the aff is limited to defending the aff framework even if the counter-framework affirms, which scoops aff ground – they are functionally floating PIKs\n\n[3] ideological flex – frameworks are by default dispo if u put defense or offer an alternative – sticking us with a framework causes ideological polarization as we are forced to defend our option even if we see its flaws – turns and outweighs the K", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · framework · 1AR] Why should we vote aff on the framework issue?", "output": "Interp: the neg may not contest the aff framework – they did\n\nVote aff –\n\n[1] Substance education – they force debate over philosophy instead of the topic – that outweighs – A] applicability – nuances over nuclear politics are hot-button topics and can be used through the rest of our life B] time frame – we only have two months but we have years and college for phil ed\n\n[2] Time skew – they moot 6 minutes of AC offense and force a 1ar restart because all my offense was contextualized to the aff – AFC checks back because I can weigh and frontline one layer – that outweighs – A] time skew is quantifiable and verifiable while other standards are speculation B] controls the internal link because we need time to make args", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · philosophical education · 2NR] Why should we vote aff based on the philosophical education argument?", "output": "Interp: the neg must concede the aff contention – they didn’t\n\nVote aff –\n\n[1] Philosophical Education – turning the aff disincentivizes phil debate which outweighs – a] constituvism – LD is values debate – this also means it’s try-or-die for phil debate because it’s dying and unique to LD b] critical thinking – thinking critically about abstract phil concepts is the best form of education that tests our minds c] small schools – contention debate is a prep game, which advantages small schools while phil debate allows analytics which is net better for smart small school debaters to focus on one arg", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · strat skew · 2NR] Why should we vote aff based on the strat skew argument?", "output": "[2] Strat skew – it moots half the aff if u turn it which forces a 1ar restart that outweighs because of devastating 1ar time skew and I can never win, which outweighs because it’s quantifiable and verifiable", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal", "flag": "warrant_only"}
{"input": "[Neg · AFC or ACC · 1AR] Why should we vote aff because the neg must concede either the aff contention or the aff framework?", "output": "The neg must concede either the aff contention or the aff framework – to clarify it’s AFC or ACC – you contested both. Vote aff –\n\n[1] Strat skew – moots all ac offense and causes a structural skew where I have to win both framework and contention – that outweighs because it’s about routes to the ballot and supercharged by the time-crunched 1ar.\n\n[2] Clash – we can either focus on phil or substance – that creates more nuanced debates where we have to contest each other’s arguments instead of overloading and spreading out the 1ar, which outweighs on constitutively being part of debate.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR shiftiness · 2NR] Why should we vote aff to deter infinite abuse from 1AR shiftiness?", "output": "Vote aff to deter infinite abuse – it means the aff always loses on theory because the 1ar could always be potentially abusive by reading 50 new a prioris or something.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · metatheory first · 2NR] Why does metatheory matter in evaluating our shell?", "output": "Metatheory first because it precludes evaluation of your shell because we’re an epistemic indict compounded by the 1ar time skew means we were skewed in responding.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · plan flaw counterplan · 1AR] Why should we vote aff for reciprocity regarding plan flaws?", "output": "Interp: If the neg claims that the aff plan has a textual flaw, they must provide a counterplan that takes the same action as the affirmative without the plan flaw – they read plan flaw without the advocacy.. Spirit over text – anything else doesn’t deter abuse and silly I-meets.\n\nVote aff for reciprocity – only the neg can read plan flaw against the aff, which is a no-risk voting issue but we can’t do it which makes it structurally irreciprocal which outweighs because it can’t be compensated by getting faster. This also straight turns their plan flaw voting issue args for education and deterrence because you teach us how to write it the right way.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · theory · 1NC] Why should we vote aff on the argument that the neg may not argue for evaluating the theory debate after the 1NC?", "output": "Interp: The neg may not argue for evaluating the [theory] debate after the 1NC – they did.\n\nVote aff –\n\n[1] Resolvability – it’s incoherent to respond to it because that assumes they get evaluated but then that would be circular which makes resolving rounds impossible and invites judge intervention to determine which args apply which is the worst form of unfairness\n\n[2] Strat skew – it means I can never respond to their args which means the neg always wins and destroys clash which is constitutive of debate", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · reasonability · 2NR] Why should we use reasonability with a brightline of strong in-round abuse on their shell?", "output": "Use reasonability with a brightline of strong in round abuse on their shell – if I prove they could engage with me, don’t vote on it. Anything else means people are incentivized to read disclosure shells that could make norms marginally better that I have almost no offense on. That OWs – a] I lose everytime because I can’t get offense on them – technically I could follow their norm and be slightly better – destroys fairness. B] Normsetting Turn – instead of disclosure mitigating actual abuse, it’s a tool to win – so people will see disclosure as frivolous and not follow norms regardless – in round abuse solves because it creates a brightline for what is worth reading disclosure on & enables enforcement of good norms.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · judge intervention · 2NR] Why does judge intervention not collapse and how does it relate to competing interpretations?", "output": "Judge intervention: a] nonunique – judges always intervene in some way through bias, and you can recotnextualize what offense is under competing interps b] there’s a clear brightline – it’s not my fault you can’t prove in round abuse [c] It doesn’t collapse - there are different types of offense/defense paradigms and CI in this case justifies winning off a marginally better norm while reasonability doesn’t.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · reasonability · 2NR] Why should we vote for you under reasonability?", "output": "Vote for me under reasonability – defense proves +", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal", "flag": "warrant_only"}
{"input": "[Neg · competing interps · 2NR] Why should we frame the competing interps debate through a lens of sufficient offense?", "output": "Frame the competing interps debate through a lens of sufficient offense - don’t let them win off marginal offense on the interp - stops people from finding very small abuse and reading theory on it, especially thru links of omissions which OW because I can’t contest drop the debater - the time I spent responding to the shell also solves.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · counterinterp · 2NR] Why should we defend the violation with a plank of open source?", "output": "I defend the violation with a plank of open source\n\n[1] solves all your abuse - you could’ve asked me before the rd to spec or structured your strat 30 mins ahead based on me not specifying - you also get way more than enough info to formulate a coherent strat.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · infinite regress · 2NR] Why does winning the theory debate justify people continuing to read regressive disclosure shells?", "output": "Infinite Regress - if they win the theory debate, it’ll justify people continuing to read regressive disclosure shells like must spec definition cites, etc. - that’s empirically proven - you should stop that now by making them lose the theory debate. Destroys fairness bc debate will devolve to people winning off to shells with marginal offense & no defense - also destroys norming bc theory will just be a race to the bottom to find these shells instead of being used to check legit abuse - ppl will hate theory - also crowds out substance.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · regress turn · 2NR] Why should we reject disclosure shells with marginal offense?", "output": "Regress Turn - Disclosure shells with marginal offense hurt disclosure norms - people will be less incentivized to disclose if they have to disclose every minute detail - it’s better for people to do disclosure 90% right than to hate it.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · reject out of round violations · 2NR] Why should we reject out of round violations and screenshots?", "output": "Reject Out of Round Violations and Screen Shots - they are non verifiable and can be subject to inspect element - that makes judges have to intervene and also justifies people lying about other’s disclosure violations - that’s unfair.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · competing interpretations · 2NR] Why should we frame the competing interps debate through a lens of sufficient offense?", "output": "Frame the competing interps debate through a lens of sufficient offense - don’t let them win off marginal offense on the interp - stops people from finding very small abuse and reading theory on it, especially thru links of omissions which OW because I can’t contest drop the debater - small abuse also outweighed by a] the time I spent beating their shell b] the bad norms they create c] proves there is no uniqueness claim", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · counterinterpretation · 2NR] Why should we defend the violation with a plank of disclosure?", "output": "Counterinterp - I defend the violation with a plank of disclosure\n\n[1] solves all your abuse - you could’ve asked me before the rd to spec or structured your strat 30 mins ahead based on me not specifying", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · infinite regress · 2NR] Why does the infinite regress argument matter in the theory debate?", "output": "[2] Infinite Regress - if they win the theory debate, it’ll justify them reading an infinite amount of shells critiquing (x practice) - their shell’s regressive - destroys fairness bc debate will devolve to people winning off to shells with marginal offense & no defense - also destroys norming bc theory will just be a race to the bottom to find these shells instead of being used to check legit abuse - ppl will hate theory - also crowds out substance.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · engagement · 2NR] What do we say to the argument that we could engage?", "output": "[3] You could engage - empirically disproven you’re doing it right now - outweighs on verifiability", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · definition choice · 2NR] Why does the definition choice argument favor us?", "output": "[4] **if for a definition** 1AR reclarification or neg definition choice solves - if anything, it makes it easier to negate - they get the 1N and 2N to win definitions while the aff only gets 1AR and 2AR", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · counterinterp · 1AR] Why should we get unidirectional paradigm issues?", "output": "Counterinterp: I get unidirectional paradigm issues.\n\nI meet\n\n1] aff flex – unique 1ar time crunch and neg reactivity means I need unique paradigm issues to compensate for that – anything else means the neg wins on theory due to the skew\n\n2] substantive education – deterring neg theory is good to allow substantive debates – outewighs on time frame – we only have 2 months to learn\n\n3] Resolvability – would mean I can’t say 1AR theory first so we couldn’t weigh between shells. That would invite intervention on arbitrarily determining a winner, which outweighs reciprocity on reversibility.\n\n4] Reject the shell on face – I shouldn’t lose for reading paradigm issues – this is functionally a counterinterp to those paradigm issues – same reason I don’t lose for losing\n\ncompeting interps vs. reasonability - also proves the shell has 0 offense as to why READING them is bad\n\n5] Reciprocity is wrong – a] time skew proves that the reciprocity is not contextual – same way inherency is a NIB b] false – you can respond to the paradigm issues themselves\n\n[6] Norming is wrong – paradigm issue debates are good –they frame evaluation of good norms. Not incoherent – I have to win aff-specific warrants – if they’re bad args beat them substantively. Fairness outweighs – most jurisdictional since the ballot says better debater and fairness controls what a good norm is.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR theory] Why should we extend our counterinterpretation on 1AR theory?", "output": "Counterinterp: The aff can say 1ar theory has those paradigm issues. I meet\n\n1] Aff flex – 1ar time crunch means I need to be able to uplayer the debate so the neg can’t get away with infinite abuse\n\n2] I shouldn’t lose for reading paradigm issues – this is functionally a counterinterp to those paradigm issues – same reason I don’t lose for losing competing interps vs. reasonability. Anything else is illogical, chills reading paradigm issues which justifies actual infinite abuse, and kills norming over their truth values - also proves the shell has 0 offense as to why READING them is bad\n\n3] No infinite abuse – A] responding to the paradigm issues substantively solves B] 2nr can win the substance of the shell with a 6 minute speech", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · CI violation] Why should we argue that their justification of winning offense under one moral index is a violation?", "output": "Violation with the plank of if they justify winning offense under one moral index being sufficient to affirm. Standard is infinite abuse - I always lose because if I concede the offense to their index, they always win under that index.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · counterinterpretation] Why should we defend the violation of the counterinterpretation?", "output": "Strat Skew - Their interpretation justifies process CPs that either slightly delay the aff or change the process, creating a possibility of the affirmative being uncertain - under their interp that would be competitive - process CPs bad they can do the aff but very slightly change one part mooting 6 mins of the 1AC\n\nCritical Thinking - forces the neg to take into account the aff’s timeline and weigh whether it’ll happen when creating things like analytics, which adds an extra layer of argumentation meaning they have to think more", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · conditionality · 2NR] Why should we argue that conditionality is good?", "output": "Counterinterp: The neg may read 1 or more conditional counterplans.\n\nConditionality is good –\n\n[1] Neg flex – the neg shouldn’t be constrained to 1 strategy – the 1nc is the first chance to make strategic decisions while the aff has infinite prep and can reclarify the plan in the 1ar. We get to test the aff from multiple angles and ensure they’re the best option from multiple angles which checks back. Condo is key to allow the negative to be strategic and not lose every round – anything else wrecks neg win percentage and good debating\n\n[2] Ideological flexibility – aff defending positions from multiple angles allows debaters to better defend their positions in the real world. OWs – a] arg justification – when you can defend the plan as a whole instead of a facet of the issue, you get better at justifying your arguments and learning interactions with multiple args b] uniqueness – modern political climates incentivize polarization to the extremes which means defending moderate ground is a key skill that is empirically in high demand but low supply now.\n\n[3] 1ar strategic thinking – condo forces the 1ar to strategically make decisions about how to respond to the counterplan, which increases critical thinking skills – outweighs all education and impact turns your fairness skews – the only way to truly learn is being able to apply prior knowledge to new situations while the only terminal impact to fairness is you whining\n\n[4] Neg Ground – if counterplans have to be uncondo, the 1nc literally has to be 7 minutes on a counterplan, destroying breadth of education and the neg’s ability to read any counterplan – it’s a double bind either a] the neg never reads a counterplan because it destroys flexibility which leads to stale debates and explodes aff win percentage because the squo is trash or b] the neg is forced to frivolously uplayer with T and theory to suck up 1nc and 1ar time if they read 1 counterplan", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Some defense · 2NR] Why should we get faster and not make life easier for the aff?", "output": "Get faster – I don’t have to make life easier", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal", "flag": "warrant_only"}
{"input": "[Neg · Some defense · 2NR] Why should we argue that all arguments are conditional and that they skew 1AR time?", "output": "All args are conditional – we don’t have to go for disads or T – non-unique – they all skew 1ar time.", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · Some defense · 2NR] Why do 2NR checks matter in terms of collapsing in the 2AR?", "output": "2NR checks – I can only go for one, so you get a 2ar collapse", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal", "flag": "warrant_only"}
{"input": "[Neg · Some defense · 2NR] Why is time skew non-unique and how does it affect reciprocity?", "output": "Time skew is non-unique – we are still making the same amount of arguments in 7 minutes and you have 4 minutes – just because they are in a different format does not make them structural abuse takes out reciprocity.", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Reciprocity · 2NR] Why do conditional permutations check abuse and how does this impact the debate?", "output": "Conditional permutations check abuse – the aff has multiple conditional worlds, this outweighs neg condo A] strategy – they get final choice of collapse-down in the 2AR and shift from the plan is the focus of the debate B] time – counterplans take 2 minutes to read while the perm takes half a second C] Burdens – we need a net benefit while the permutation does not. And, even if kicking counterplans means perms go away, a world where counterplans must be unconditional, then the permutation becomes the same as conditionality, which means the weighing all still applies and straight turns their abuse story.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Reciprocity · 2NR]", "output": "Reciprocity is not an impact – a] you have 3 speeches and I have 2 so reciprocity is contingent upon circumstances b] you have burdens like inherency and topicality which are not reciprocal but necessary", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Reciprocity · 2NR]", "output": "You can kick aff advantages – we should be able to kick counterplans", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal", "flag": "warrant_only"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Reciprocity · 2NR]", "output": "Not structural abuse – you simply have to tailor your arguments to take out the CP and the squo – if your aff is not the best option, that’s your fault", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Clash · 2NR]", "output": "No impact – clash is inevitable because we debate over arguments", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Clash · 2NR]", "output": "Absurd – this would say the neg would have to take the route of most resistance every time, which destroy strategic thinking and debate as a competitive game", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Clash · 2NR]", "output": "Turn – we have more clash in multiple areas, which outweighs on breadth of education", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Time Skew · 2NR]", "output": "Conditional permutations check abuse – the aff has multiple conditional worlds, this outweighs neg condo A] strategy – they get final choice of collapse-down in the 2AR and shift from the plan is the focus of the debate B] time – counterplans take 2 minutes to read while the perm takes half a second C] Burdens – we need a net benefit while the permutation does not", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Time Skew · 2NR]", "output": "Turn – condo allows the aff to use one aff advantage to take out multiple neg worlds – if you wrote your aff strategically, only the plan would solve, which should take out the CP and the squo", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Time Skew · 2NR]", "output": "No impact – we both have 13 minutes", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · AT Time Skew · 2NR] Why do 2AR checks matter even if the arguments are not the best?", "output": "2AR checks – Even if your args were not the best, you can sit on a few and collapse and weigh to check back any substantive flaws", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · policy making education] Why should we defend the nuances of our plan in its entirety?", "output": "Policy making education-- policy makers slightly alter plans to produce the best consequences, so you should be able to defend the nuances of your plan in its entirety", "category": "Case", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · neg flex] Why do we need PICs to check back against the AC?", "output": "Neg flex-- neg forced to be reactive and AC has infinite prep time to frontline the 1ar, so I need PICs to check back", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · perms solve] Why can we make cheaty severance perms?", "output": "perms solve-- you can make cheaty severance perms", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal", "flag": "warrant_only"}
{"input": "[Neg · I-meet · 2NR] Why should we extend the I-meet argument?", "output": "First extend the I-meet – He has conceded my contact info is on the wiki page. There is no contestation from the 1AR that I have my contact info on my wiki. I have my contact info disclosed on the wiki – if you scroll down you see the email I use to alter all my documents. That meets because all their interpretation says is that I have to have a form of contact info on my wiki, which I do.\n\nHere’s the impact to the I-Meet: You can’t vote aff on an interp I don’t violate. It doesn’t matter what he says on the standard level. Me winning the I-meet means you auto negate absent ANY of their arguments on the standard level.\n\nTheir arguments about why email generally doesn’t solve don’t apply to the i-meet – the interpretation just says that I have to have MY contact info disclosed, and I do – even if that might not be a good way for other people to disclose their contact info, it solves for me. Obviously violations have to be specific to ME because otherwise people can read theory on things you don’t violate. By the way, I not only obviously meet the text of the interp and I obviously meet the spirit – the spirit should be that you should be able to go on my wiki and find out how to contact me and you can. Everyone in the world knows how to scroll down. They’re going to go for some BS spirit over text spin, but they haven’t justified why I violate spirit and why spirit comes over text, but either way I’ll win text over spirit anyways.\n\n[1] Verifiability - no way to determine the spirit of an argument, we only have the text two impacts [a] makes the round irresolvable because the judge doesnt know what it means to evaluate spirit [b] infinite abuse - you will just say the spirit is something completely different and I’ll always violate something I don’t.\n\n[2] Double bind - either [a] its okay to let the judge evaluate arguments that weren't actually made, thus you evaluate 100 theory shells I didn’t make with drop the debater that come before disclosure or [b] it isn't ok which means you don't evaluate the spirit given that you never said in your original speech what constituted it.\n\nEven if I’m not winning the i-meet, all the arguments I made on it still solve nearly all of his offense. You could’ve just scrolled down on my wiki. That means the things like messenger which around 99 percent of the debate community know about, There are hundreds of ways to ensure clash that don’t involve their supposed interpretation – or scrolling down for 3 seconds which is a skill every debater should probably have, finding a teammate’s email – literally every one of these ensure clash.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · disclosure · 1NC] Why should we vote neg for prep and clash based on the violation of disclosure?", "output": "Interpretation—the affirmative debater must disclose the text of the framing mechanism and the advocacy text to the negative debater 30 minutes before the round or once pairings come out if pairings come out within 30 minutes of the round. To clarify, disclosure can occur on the wiki or over message.\n\nViolation—they didn’t – screenshots\n\nVote neg for prep and clash—two internal links—a) neg prep—4 minutes of prep is not enough to put together a coherent 1nc or update generics—30 minutes is necessary to learn a little about the affirmative and piece together what 1nc positions apply and cut and research their applications to the affirmative b) aff quality—plan text disclosure discourages cheap shot affs. If the aff isn’t inherent or easily defeated by 20 minutes of research, it should lose—this will answer the 1ar’s claim about innovation—with 30 minutes of prep, there’s still an incentive to find a new strategic, well justified aff, but no incentive to cut a horrible, incoherent aff that the neg can’t check against the broader literature.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · bidirectional interps] Why should we reject bidirectional interpretations?", "output": "Bidirectional interps bad – interps like ACC or straight ref bad are purely for strategic purposes b/c debaters just read them when rounds are hard – o/w – kills norming b/c we won’t have a clear set of rules under which to debate.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR voting issues] Why should we reject 1AR voting issues?", "output": "A. Aff gets infinite prep time before the AC, frames the debate, and gets the 2AR to frame the judge’s ballot. Infinite prep o/w TS – they can script 1AR’s to perfection.\nB. Aff can be super abusive in the 1AR and judges are much more reluctant to vote on 2N theory because of the 6-3 time skew.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR theory] Why should we reject 1AR theory?", "output": "They can just blow up dropped arguments in the next speech making it impossible for me to win since I only have the 2n.\nAff gets to speak first and last and gets infinite pre-round prep time; new layers in the 1AR just exacerbate the skew.\nResolvability - every round dissolve to see if the judge thinks the 2ar answers to the 2n are good enough which means they have to inject bias.\n1~ The 2NR must overcover theory since they get 3 minute 2AR collapse on one of the layers and persuasiveness advantage of a 3 minute 2AR.\n\n2~ Responses to my counter interp will be new which means 1AR theory necessitates intervention—outweighs because it makes the decision arbitrary.\n\n3~ I only have one chance to respond after it is introduced while they have two chances.\n\n4~ Deters the 1NC from checking abuse out of fear for 1AR meta-theory, which destroys me since it's also preclusive. Turns their infinite abuse args.\n\n5~ Resolvability double bind—either you automatically accept 2AR responses to 2NR counter-standards which means they always win since I can't answer those responses, or you have to intervene to determine the credence you give those 2AR responses, which makes it irresolvable and unfair.\n\n6~ Reject infinite abuse claims—a~ spikes solve—there are only so many theoretical issues anyway, b~ infinite abuse doesn't exist since there are a finite number of rounds, c~ if I win I can't engage in 1AR theory then you could never check infinite abuse since we can't use your shells to determine what's abusive d. Functional limits solves – I only have 7 minutes so I can’t be infinitely abusive.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · negating is harder] Why is negating inherently harder?", "output": "Aff has the ability to read the first framework and spikes which I have to coincide with and react to which outweighs since a) you have infinite prep time to frontline your aff before round so you’ll always be ahead of me and b) this turns my ability to react since you can mold my advocacy until I’m forced into generics that you are ready to debate.\nYou speak first and last which means you have a psychological judge persuasion advantage since you frame the round in their mind and are the last thing they remember.\nThis means I get presumption and neg flex on theory because it’s inherently harder to debate my side.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · theory debate evaluation · 2NR] Why should we evaluate the theory debate after the 2NR instead of the 2AR?", "output": "Evaluate the theory debate after the 2NR, not the 2AR: 1) I have no 3NR, so evaluating the theory debate after the 2AR puts me at a structural disadvantage since I can’t point out 2AR argument shifts or extrapolations and to respond to new 2AR arguments. 2) Time skew: the aff has 7 minutes of speech time between the 3 minute 2AR and 4 minute 1AR, while I only have a 6 minute 2NR. At worst, even if you don’t structurally preclude new 2AR arguments, this means you should err neg on the theory debate if it’s close to counterbalance the aff advantage.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 2AR theory weighing · 2NR] Why is 2AR theory weighing always illegitimate?", "output": "2AR theory weighing is always illegitimate because the aff would always win 2AR theory debates--I have no 3NR and conceded arguments are assumed true. They had the chance to weigh in the 1AR--for example, by taking a stance on fairness vs. education--and didn’t do it.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · RVI's in 2NR · 2NR] Why should we grant 2NR RVI's?", "output": "At worst, grant 2NR RVI’s because the 1AR can uplayer nullifying all previous NC offence and I don’t have time to deal with multiple shells and substance.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1NC theory before 1AR · 2NR] Why is it justified for me to read an abusive position in response to aff abuse?", "output": "1NC theory before 1AR theory- Neg abuse if justified by aff abuse, the only way for me to compensate for the existing disadvantages was to read an abusive position myself, don’t drop me for trying to compensate for a disadvantage.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · interpretation of actor in sanctions · 2NR] Why should we require the affirmative to specify the actor that eliminates economic sanctions?", "output": "Interpretation – the affirmative must specify the actor that eliminates economic sanctions.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · violation of actor specification · 2NR] Why is it a violation if the affirmative doesn’t specify the actor?", "output": "Violation- They don’t. US Doesn’t cut it too many definitions A] Federal Government.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · 1AR shift · 2NR] Why should we reject the 1AR shift argument?", "output": "1. Ground – the aff doesn’t provide an agent which ought to enact the plan – that strips the neg of agent DAs, process CPs, nuanced K links, and numerous case answers. We’re forced to defend what they’re most prepped on – sanctions good – meaning infinite aff prep causes them to win every round.\n\n2. 1AR shift – the 1AR can re-define normal means and they have authority over what their plan entails. We’re forced to get unverifiable cross-x agreements and pre-emptively not read most of our offense because the 1AR can moot it, and the 2NR can’t restart.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · new paradigm issues · 2NR] Why should we reject new paradigm issues after the 1NC?", "output": "Neither side should get new paradigm issues after the 1NC- A] It incentivizes endless sandbagging in the 1AR splitting the 2NR B] 1NC has already occurred with current paradigm issues in mind C] introducing them in the aff allows for them to be more rigorously tested", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · competing interps · 2NR] Why should we reject the competing interpretations argument?", "output": "1] Reasonability is arbitrary\n\n2] It’s key to norming\n\n3] It collapses-since you use an offense defense paradigm to evaluate brightlines", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · DTD on DTA · 2NR] Why should we reject DTA?", "output": "DTD—DTA doesn’t make sense and it’s key to deterring abuse", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · no RVI · 2NR] Why should we reject the no RVI argument?", "output": "1] Illogical- shouldn’t win for being fair---o/w because it’s a litmus test for argumentation\n\n2] Incentivizes theory baiting\n\n3] Chills debaters from going for theory\n\n4] Counter interp-with the brightline of 2 shells solves their offense since it means they don’t have to spend much time on theory", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · drop the debater] Why should we drop the debater?", "output": "a) they have a 7-6 rebuttal advantage and the 2ar to make args I can’t respond to, b) it deters future abuse and sets a positive norm.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · use competing interps] Why should we use competing interpretations?", "output": "a) reasonability invites arbitrary judge intervention since we don’t know your bs meter, b) collapses to competing interps – we justify 2 brightlines under an offense defense paradigm just like 2 interps.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · no RVIs] Why should we reject RVIs?", "output": "a) illogical – you shouldn’t win for being fair – it’s a litmus test for engaging in substance, b) norming – I can’t concede the counterinterp if I realize I’m wrong which forces me to argue for bad norms, c) chilling effect – forces you to split your 2AR so you can’t collapse and misconstrue the 2NR, d) topic ed – prevents 1AR blipstorm scripts and allows us to get back to substance after resolving theory.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · interpretation] Why should the affirmative provide a counter-solvency advocate if they defend anything other than the resolution?", "output": "If the affirmative defends anything other than 'The United States ought to end its use of economic sanctions,' then they must provide a counter-solvency advocate for their specific advocacy. (To clarify, you must have an author that states we should not do your aff, insofar as the aff is not a whole res phil aff)", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · fairness · 2NR] Why should we prioritize fairness as a voter in this debate?", "output": "Fairness is a voter since it’s constitutive of debate and comes before education since if I can’t engage w/ the aff there’s no way to get any education. Jurisdiction is a voter since judges can’t vote on the aff if it wasn’t topical.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · limits · 2NR] Why should we argue that limits are important for substantive engagement?", "output": "Operating outside the bounds of the general maxim places an infinite research burden, narrowing the plans to ones with counter-solvency advocates ensures good substantive engagement since it guarantees both sides, and narrows out trivially true advocacies.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · research · 2NR] Why does our argument about research matter for the aff's position?", "output": "Forces the aff to go to the other side of the library and contest their own viewpoints, as well as encouraging in-depth research about their own position. Having one also encourages more in-depth answers since I can find responses. Key to education since we definitionally learn more about positions when we contest our own.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · competing interpretations · 2NR] Why should we reject reasonability in favor of competing interpretations?", "output": "A] theory is a yes/no question, you can’t be reasonably fair B] reasonability is arbitrary and invites judge intervention C] reasonability causes a race to the bottom.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · no RVIs · 2NR] Why should we reject RVIs in this debate?", "output": "1] Encourages theory baiting and chills checking real abuse. 2] Illogical b/c don’t win for being fair and logic is meta-constraint on arguments b/c comes lexically prior. 3] Double Bind – Either my theory shell is a] unwarranted and should be easy to respond to or b] stands because there is actual abuse in the round.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · interpretation · 2NR] Why should the aff clarify the role of the ballot in their 1AC?", "output": "The aff must explicitly specify a comprehensive role of the ballot in the form of a text in the 1AC where they clarify how offense links back to the role of the ballot, such as whether post-fiat offense or pre-fiat offense matters and what constitutes that offense with implications on how to weigh.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · role of the ballot · 2NR] Why should we link turn the role of the ballot?", "output": "Link turns your role of the ballot – your impacts are premised on actually having a debate and engaging with issues of oppression. Almost impossible to engage roles of the ballot are uniquely bad since no one will take seriously a position that can’t be clashed with, so you harm any progress your position can create.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · strategy skew · 2NR] Why does strategy skew matter?", "output": "Strategy Skew – You make formulating a strategy impossible since I don’t know what links to your evaluative mechanism. My interp means we know what a legitimate neg advocacy is, otherwise you can make up reasons mine doesn’t link to the role of the ballot in the next speech, and by specing a weighing mechanism I can know to make the most relevant arguments so you can’t arbitrarily preclude them in the next speech.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · education as a voter · 2NR] Why should we consider education a voter?", "output": "Education is a voter because it’s the only reason schools fund debate.", "category": "Framework", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Aff · Yes Act-Omission Distinction] Why should we reject the act-omission distinction?", "output": "1] Infinite obligations – no act-omission means you’re culpable for every omission which is untenable: you could be curing cancer right now. Answering this negates – (a) The 1AC is suboptimal compared to some alternative like consulting, process differences or a tweak in enforcement (b) State action freezes because they wouldn’t be able to decide between alternatives, triggering presumption.\n\n2] Trolley Problem – Omissions allow us to escape culpability in otherwise unavoidable situations like when someone pulls the lever to kill 1 instead of 2 – otherwise we’re always wrong which makes morality inaccessible – outweighs on bindingness – if an agent is permanently violating ethics, they can’t take moral action.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · act-omission] How do we respond to the argument that omitting ethical actions is not permissible?", "output": "1] The US not implementing a single payer universal healthcare is a legitimate action because omitting ethical actions is always permissible.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · determinism] Why does determinism deny the existence of obligations?", "output": "Determinism denies the existence of obligations because you can’t hold agents culpable for actions external to their free will since they would occur regardless of whether it was good or bad.\n\nCausal Link Chains – if all consequences are triggered by prior actions, then all actions are triggered by prior consequences, which proves a causal chain of events structure action rather than free will.\n\nBrain Activity – their bindingness warrants are all reasons why, biologically speaking, our brains are hard wired to pursue pleasure and reject pain. Our bodies take actions based off brain activity, which we have zero control over, which disproves free will.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · induction fails] Why should we reject the use of induction to justify actions?", "output": "Induction fails – we can’t use the past to justify actions since it assumes those exact past events will happen the same way. Saying predictions are accurate is circular since that uses inductive reasoning to justify induction.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · consequences] Why does the lack of a cutoff for consequences matter?", "output": "There’s no cutoff for when a consequence ends which leads to endless causal chains with infinite consequences.\n\nWe only know a consequence will occur after it happens which means it can’t guide prior action.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · desires and consequences] Why is it important that we can choose different consequences?", "output": "We can simply stop pursuing our desires of certain consequences and look to different ones, means it’s escapable and circular.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · information and prediction] Why does the shifting nature of circumstances affect our ability to predict consequences?", "output": "Circumstances are always shifting and we don’t know what affects or doesn’t affect our ability to collect sufficient information to predict consequences, so our calculations require infinitely more calculation, which halts action.", "category": "Kritik", "mode": "normal"}
